<br>
Well Kimaya, for people like you with high innate wisdom this might work. But unfortunately there are some mage-like people around like me who have to rely on their intellect.<br>
Obviously this poem isn't about finding the right questions, rather it says (as you have hinted before also): Better don't ask at all!<br>
Well, that's a fascinating idea. But this path dulls the intellect, senses and ambitions. You can solve all the questions by saying 'Do you really want an answer?' and secretly hinting that questions shouldn't be asked at all, you can solve all problems with our feelings we have by saying 'Do you really need those feelings?' and secretly hinting that we shouldn't have any desires at all.<br>
Is this neutral? Yes, maybe. But is this actually anything at all?<br>
It maybe works for you, and you do well. But I have a different philosophy.<br>
For example:<br>
I assume you would say: Not-knowing is true knowledge. (OOC: 71)<br>
I would rather say: What you know, you know, what you don't know, you don't know. This is knowledge. <br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.human.toyogakuen-u.ac.jp/~acmuller/contao/analects.htm">(OOC: see here, 2:17)</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Struggle on these questions is useless, and not necessary.<br>
Let's be friends and be happy!<br>
*hugs Kimaya*<br>
