Can you sense it ? It would be the worst of fates, if the world actually came to *that*. No, Ellywig, that is no utopia. It is the opposite. I would never want to live in a world like that. Perhaps that is why i rarely go there.<br>
<br>
And to Kimaya, well, i could write many words. But Teiraa did it so well, once more. So i will merely point out the one part of the little poem, which i can actually understand.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
If you keep your mind from judging<br>
and aren't led by the senses,<br>
your heart will find peace.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
To me, that reads.. if you do not judge, do not act, do not decide, you will find peace. So, peace is found in inaction - in watching - in doing nothing. So, if all follow that, everything will be in peace. And noone will do, noone will act, noone will move, beause all found peace. And the morning after, Norrath would be quiet, because all would have found eternal peace - the peace of death.<br>
<br>
No, Kimaya, i think that poem is far more cruel than i could ever be. It offers a sollution, but only for a few. If all heed it, and all follow it, the result will be stagnation and death. The quiet of nothing ever changing.<br>
<br>
So, call me lovelyscritch.. or sillyscritch.. or whatever you like - but i still see what you offer as a fate worse than what Zildrax offered.<br>
<br>
Oh, and a side note, Zildrax: Of course they will sooner or later invade the Iksar ruins.  If they wont, others will. And all those which will not succumb to hatred will be sacrificed. <p>Silenae Do'Bauthin<br><br>
